#
# apps/capture/Kconfig
#
# Capture library: a thin userspace wrapper around the kernel chardev
# /dev/btcap (Issue #122).  Used by apps/sensor's `do_capture` and any
# future capture client.  Has no MAIN/builtin of its own; toggling this
# Kconfig just builds the helpers into the apps library.
#

config APP_CAPTURE
	tristate "Userspace capture library (Issue #122)"
	default n
	depends on BOARD_BTCAP_CHARDEV
	---help---
		Wrapper around /dev/btcap that exposes the four-function
		capture lifecycle (init / write / deinit / abort) plus the
		.cap file header builder.  capture clients link this library
		statically; the library itself produces no NSH builtin.

if APP_CAPTURE

config APP_CAPTURE_MAX_HANDLES
	int "Maximum concurrent capture handles in this build"
	default 1
	---help---
		Process-wide cap on simultaneously active capture_init() calls.
		v1 ships with 1 (single-client, single-session) per the design;
		this knob is here so a future feature can bump it without
		touching every caller.  Library will reject capture_init beyond
		this count with -EMFILE.

config APP_CAPTURE_MAX_HEAP_BYTES
	int "Default heap budget per capture invocation (bytes)"
	default 65536
	---help---
		Advisory upper bound that capture clients (apps/sensor) use
		when sizing their malloc() for a capture buffer.  Set to a
		value that fits the worst-case usram budget on the target
		board.  The library itself does not enforce this — it is
		surfaced here so all clients agree on the same default.

		On spike-prime-hub the user heap has ~100 KB free at idle so
		64 KB is safe for a single in-flight session.  At 100 Hz with
		a 9 B record this lets `sensor color capture` go for ~72 s.

endif # APP_CAPTURE
